Program Intention :
===============================================================================================
Allocates memory like malloc( ), but terminates on failure.


===============================================================================================
COMPILE :
make
gcc -Wall -g -o pg266_xmalloc pg266_xmalloc.c;

===============================================================================================
Execution:

linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg266_xmalloc$ ./pg266_xmalloc

 succesfull xmalloc()
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg266_xmalloc$

===============================================================================================
Program Flow
===============================================================================================
    use of  malloc() wrapper that prints an error message and terminates the program if 
    malloc( ) returns NULL . 
    By convention, developers call this common wrapper xmalloc( )




